{"cursor":"53642","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"[[Image:PeakWaterAquifer.PNG|thumb|300px|Potential peak water curve for\nproduction of groundwater from an aquifer. {{cite web\n|url=http://www.worldwater.org/data20082009/ch01.pdf |title=The World's Water\n2008-2009, Ch 1. |publisher=Pacific Institute |author=Meena Palaniappan and\nPeter H. Gleick |year=2008 |accessdate=2009-01-31 }} ]] The term 'Peak\nWater' has been put forward as a concept to help understand growing constraints\non the availability, quality, and use of freshwater resources. The clearest\ndefinitions of the term were laid out in a 2010 peer-reviewed article in the\nProceedings of the National Academy of Sciences by Peter Gleick and Meena\nPalaniappan. {{cite journal\n|url=http://www.pnas.org/cgi/doi/10.1073/pnas.1004812107 |author=Gleick, P.H.,\nM. Palaniappan. |date=2010-6 |title=Peak Water: Conceptual and Practical Limits\nto Freshwater Withdrawal and Use. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy\nof Sciences |volume= 107 |issue= 25 |pages=11155â11162\n|doi=10.1073/pnas.1004812107 }} They define peak renewable, peak non-\nrenewable, and peak ecological water. There is a vast amount of water on the\nplanet but sustainably managed water is becoming scarce. {{cite web\n|url=http://www.worldwater.org |title=The World's Water 2008-2009: The Biennial\nReport of Freshwater Resources (Pacific Institute) |publisher=Island Press,\nWashington D.C. |year=2009 |accessdate=2009-01-26 }} An updated assessment\nwas published in August 2011 in the Stockholm International Water Institute's\njournal. {{cite journal |url=http://www.-\nsiwi.org/documents/Resources/Best/2010/2011_OTWF_Peter_Gleick.pdf\n|author=Gleick, P. and M. Palaniappan. |date=2011-08 |title=On the Waterfront\n|journal=Water Resources |volume=2 |pages=41â49 }} Much of the world's\nwater in underground aquifers {{cite web\n|url=http://www.uswaternews.com/archives/arcsupply/6worllarg2.html\n|title=World's largest aquifer going dry |publisher=US Water News |date=2006-02\n|accessdate=2009-01-26 }} and in lakes {{cite web |url=http://www.earth-\npolicy.org/Updates/2005/Update47_data.htm |title=Disappearing Lakes, Shrinking\nSeas: Selected Examples |publisher=Earth Policy Institute |date= |accessdate=2009-01-\n26 }} behaves like a finite resource by being depleted. The phrase peak\nwater sparks debates similar to those about peak oil. The concept has sparked\nsuch high interest that The New York Times chose the phrase \"peak water\" as one\nof their 33 \"Words of the Year\" for 2010. {{cite web\n|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/19/weekinreview/19sifton.html\n|author=Sifton, Sam and Grant Barrett. |date=2010-12-18 |title=The Words of the\nYear |publisher=The New York Times }}\n\nThere is concern that the state of peak water is being approached in many areas\naround the world. Some areas are suffering from peak renewable water, where\nentire renewable flows are being consumed for human use, 'peak non-renewable'\nwater, where groundwater aquifers are being overpumped (or contaminated) faster\nthan nature recharges them (this example is most like the peak oil debate), and\npeak ecological water, where ecological and environmental constraints are\noverwhelming the economic benefits provided by water use. If present trends continue, 1.8 billion\npeople will be living with absolute water scarcity by 2025, and two thirds of\nthe world population could be subject to water stress. {{cite\nweb |url=http://www.unep.org/geo/geo4/report/GEO-4_Report_Full_en.pdf\n|title=Global Environmental Outlook - GEO4 environment for development\n|publisher=United Nations Environment Programme |page=97 |year=2007 |format=PDF\n|accessdate=2009-02-01 }} Ultimately, peak water is not about running out\nof fresh water, but about reaching physical, economic, and environmental limits\non meeting human demands for water and the subsequent decline of water\navailability and use.\n","linknr":805,"url":"Peak_water","recor